ional indoor suburban shopping mall, that icon of modern American capitalism and culture, is being replaced by outdoor retail centers. Yet the law and courts have been slow to catch up. Maniscalco argues that scholars, students, and the public must confront these innovations in commercial design and consumer practices, as well as what they portend for contemporary metropolitan America and its civic spaces.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aFreedom of expressionzUnited States. 0aFreedom of expression--United States. 0aShopping centersxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 4aPolitics and Law : Constitutional Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Theory. 4aSociology : Geography. 4aSociology : Urban Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civil Rights.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2015z978311149061840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143845845840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438458458423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438458458/original  a978-3-11-149061-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles